# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: webrtc-datachannel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:webrtc-datachannel/datagram-transport-layer-security] DTLS 1.0 is based on TLS 1.1, DTLS 1.2 is based on TLS 1.2, and DTLS 1.3 is based on TLS 1.3.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/datagram-transport-layer-security] There is no DTLS 1.1 because this version-number was skipped in order to harmonize version numbers with TLS.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/datagram-transport-layer-security] Like previous DTLS versions, DTLS 1.3 is intended to provide "equivalent security guarantees [to TLS 1.3] with the exception of order protection/non-replayability".
[src:webrtc-datachannel/datagram-transport-layer-security] In February 2013 two researchers from Royal Holloway, University of London discovered a timing attack which allowed them to recover (parts of the) plaintext from a DTLS connection using the OpenSSL or GnuTLS implementation of DTLS when Cipher Block Chaining mode encryption was used.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/interactive-connectivity-establishment] ICE is developed by the Internet Engineering Task Force MMUSIC working group and is published as RFC 8445, as of August 2018, and has obsolesced both RFC 5245 and RFC 4091.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/interactive-connectivity-establishment] Network address translation (NAT) became an effective technique in delaying the exhaustion of the available address pool of Internet Protocol version 4, which is inherently limited to around four billion unique addresses.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/interactive-connectivity-establishment] NAT gateways track outbound requests from a private network and maintain the state of each established connection to later direct responses from the peer on the public network to the peer in the private network, which would otherwise not be directly addressable.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/interactive-connectivity-establishment] VoIP, peer-to-peer, and many other applications require address information of communicating peers within the data streams of the connection, rather than only in the Internet Protocol packet headers.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/interactive-connectivity-establishment] For example, the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) communicates the IP address of network clients for registration with a location service, so that telephone calls may be routed to registered clients.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/interactive-connectivity-establishment] ICE provides a framework with which a communicating peer may discover and communicate its public IP address so that it can be reached by other peers.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/interactive-connectivity-establishment] Session Traversal Utilities for NAT (STUN) is a standardized protocol for such address discovery including NAT classification.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/interactive-connectivity-establishment] Traversal Using Relays around NAT (TURN) places a third-party server to relay messages between two clients when direct media traffic between peers is not allowed by a firewall.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In contrast, the traditional client–server model assigns resource provider and requester roles to different participants, with centralized servers acting as providers and clients acting as requesters.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] While P2P systems had previously been used in many application domains, the architecture was popularized by the Internet file sharing system Napster, originally released in 1999.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] P2P is used in many protocols such as BitTorrent file sharing over the Internet and in personal networks like Miracast displaying and Bluetooth radio.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The concept has inspired new structures and philosophies in many areas of human interaction.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In such social contexts, peer-to-peer as a meme refers to the egalitarian social networking that has emerged throughout society, enabled by Internet technologies in general.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] While P2P systems had previously been used in many application domains, the concept was popularized by file sharing systems such as the music-sharing application Napster.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The peer-to-peer movement allowed millions of Internet users to connect "directly, forming groups and collaborating to become user-created search engines, virtual supercomputers, and filesystems".
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The basic concept of peer-to-peer computing was envisioned in earlier software systems and networking discussions, reaching back to principles stated in the first Request for Comments, RFC 1.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Tim Berners-Lee's vision for the World Wide Web was close to a P2P network in that it assumed each user of the web would be an active editor and contributor, creating and linking content to form an interlinked "web" of links.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The early Internet was more open than the present day, where two machines connected to the Internet could send packets to each other without firewalls and other security measures.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] This contrasts with the broadcasting-like structure of the web as it has developed over the years.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] As a precursor to the Internet, ARPANET was a successful peer-to-peer network where "every participating node could request and serve content".
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Therefore, Usenet, a distributed messaging system that is often described as an early peer-to-peer architecture, was established.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] It was developed in 1979 as a system that enforces a decentralized model of control.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The basic model is a client–server model from the user or client perspective that offers a self-organizing approach to newsgroup servers.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] However, news servers communicate with one another as peers to propagate Usenet news articles over the entire group of network servers.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The same consideration applies to SMTP email in the sense that the core email-relaying network of mail transfer agents has a peer-to-peer character, while the periphery of Email clients and their direct connections is strictly a client-server relationship.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In May 1999, with millions more people on the Internet, Shawn Fanning introduced the music and file-sharing application called Napster.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Napster was the beginning of peer-to-peer networks, as we know them today, where "participating users establish a virtual network, entirely independent from the physical network, without having to obey any administrative authorities or restrictions".
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Peer-to-peer networks generally implement some form of virtual overlay network on top of the physical network topology, where the nodes in the overlay form a subset of the nodes in the physical network.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Data is still exchanged directly over the underlying TCP/IP network, but at the application layer peers can communicate with each other directly, via the logical overlay links (each of which corresponds to a path through the underlying physical network).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Overlays are used for indexing and peer discovery, and make the P2P system independent from the physical network topology.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Based on how the nodes are linked to each other within the overlay network, and how resources are indexed and located, we can classify networks as *unstructured* or *structured* (or as a hybrid between the two).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Because there is no structure globally imposed upon them, unstructured networks are easy to build and allow for localized optimizations to different regions of the overlay.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Also, because the role of all peers in the network is the same, unstructured networks are highly robust in the face of high rates of "churn"—that is, when large numbers of peers are frequently joining and leaving the network.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] However, the primary limitations of unstructured networks also arise from this lack of structure.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In particular, when a peer wants to find a desired piece of data in the network, the search query must be flooded through the network to find as many peers as possible that share the data.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Flooding causes a very high amount of signaling traffic in the network, uses more CPU/memory (by requiring every peer to process all search queries), and does not ensure that search queries will always be resolved.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Furthermore, since there is no correlation between a peer and the content managed by it, there is no guarantee that flooding will find a peer that has the desired data.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Popular content is likely to be available at several peers and any peer searching for it is likely to find the same thing.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] But if a peer is looking for rare data shared by only a few other peers, then it is highly unlikely that the search will be successful.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In *structured peer-to-peer networks* the overlay is organized into a specific topology, and the protocol ensures that any node can efficiently search the network for a file/resource, even if the resource is extremely rare.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The most common type of structured P2P networks implement a distributed hash table (DHT), in which a variant of consistent hashing is used to assign ownership of each file to a particular peer.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] This enables peers to search for resources on the network using a hash table: that is, (*key*, *value*) pairs are stored in the DHT, and any participating node can efficiently retrieve the value associated with a given key.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] However, in order to route traffic efficiently through the network, nodes in a structured overlay must maintain lists of neighbors that satisfy specific criteria.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] This makes them less robust in networks with a high rate of *churn* (i.e. with large numbers of nodes frequently joining and leaving the network).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] More recent evaluation of P2P resource discovery solutions under real workloads have pointed out several issues in DHT-based solutions such as high cost of advertising/discovering resources and static and dynamic load imbalance.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Notable distributed networks that use DHTs include Tixati, an alternative to BitTorrent's distributed tracker, the Kad network, the Storm botnet, and the YaCy.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Some prominent research projects include the Chord project, Kademlia, PAST storage utility, P-Grid, a self-organized and emerging overlay network, and CoopNet content distribution system.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] DHT-based networks have also been widely utilized for accomplishing efficient resource discovery for grid computing systems, as it aids in resource management and scheduling of applications.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Hybrid models are a combination of peer-to-peer and client–server models.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] A common hybrid model is to have a central server that helps peers find each other.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Spotify was an example of a hybrid model [until 2014].
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] There are a variety of hybrid models, all of which make trade-offs between the centralized functionality provided by a structured server/client network and the node equality afforded by the pure peer-to-peer unstructured networks.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Currently, hybrid models have better performance than either pure unstructured networks or pure structured networks because certain functions, such as searching, do require a centralized functionality but benefit from the decentralized aggregation of nodes provided by unstructured networks.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Peer-to-peer systems pose unique challenges from a computer security perspective.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Like any other form of software, P2P applications can contain vulnerabilities.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] What makes this particularly dangerous for P2P software, however, is that peer-to-peer applications act as servers as well as clients, meaning that they can be more vulnerable to remote exploits.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Since each node plays a role in routing traffic through the network, malicious users can perform a variety of "routing attacks", or denial of service attacks.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The prevalence of malware varies between different peer-to-peer protocols.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Studies analyzing the spread of malware on P2P networks found, for example, that 63% of the answered download requests on the gnutella network contained some form of malware, whereas only 3% of the content on OpenFT contained malware.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In both cases, the top three most common types of malware accounted for the large majority of cases (99% in gnutella, and 65% in OpenFT).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Another study analyzing traffic on the Kazaa network found that 15% of the 500,000 file sample taken were infected by one or more of the 365 different computer viruses that were tested for.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Corrupted data can also be distributed on P2P networks by modifying files that are already being shared on the network.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] For example, on the FastTrack network, the RIAA managed to introduce faked chunks into downloads and downloaded files (mostly MP3 files).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Files infected with the RIAA virus were unusable afterwards and contained malicious code.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The RIAA is also known to have uploaded fake music and movies to P2P networks in order to deter illegal file sharing.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Consequently, the P2P networks of today have seen an enormous increase of their security and file verification mechanisms.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Modern hashing, chunk verification and different encryption methods have made most networks resistant to almost any type of attack, even when major parts of the respective network have been replaced by faked or nonfunctional hosts.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The decentralized nature of P2P networks increases robustness because it removes the single point of failure that can be inherent in a client–server based system.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] As nodes arrive and demand on the system increases, the total capacity of the system also increases, and the likelihood of failure decreases.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] If one peer on the network fails to function properly, the whole network is not compromised or damaged.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In contrast, in a typical client–server architecture, clients share only their demands with the system, but not their resources.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In this case, as more clients join the system, fewer resources are available to serve each client, and if the central server fails, the entire network is taken down.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] There are both advantages and disadvantages in P2P networks related to the topic of data backup, recovery, and availability.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In a centralized network, the system administrators are the only forces controlling the availability of files being shared.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] If the administrators decide to no longer distribute a file, they simply have to remove it from their servers, and it will no longer be available to users.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Along with leaving the users powerless in deciding what is distributed throughout the community, this makes the entire system vulnerable to threats and requests from the government and other large forces.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] For example, YouTube has been pressured by the RIAA, MPAA, and entertainment industry to filter out copyrighted content.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Although server-client networks are able to monitor and manage content availability, they can have more stability in the availability of the content they choose to host.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] A client should not have trouble accessing obscure content that is being shared on a stable centralized network.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] P2P networks, however, are more unreliable in sharing unpopular files because sharing files in a P2P network requires that at least one node in the network has the requested data, and that node must be able to connect to the node requesting the data.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] This requirement is occasionally hard to meet because users may delete or stop sharing data at any point.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In a P2P network, the community of users is entirely responsible for deciding which content is available.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Unpopular files eventually disappear and become unavailable as fewer people share them.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Popular files, however, are highly and easily distributed.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Popular files on a P2P network are more stable and available than files on central networks.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In a centralized network, a simple loss of connection between the server and clients can cause a failure, but in P2P networks, the connections between every node must be lost to cause a data-sharing failure.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In a centralized system, the administrators are responsible for all data recovery and backups, while in P2P systems, each node requires its backup system.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Because of the lack of central authority in P2P networks, forces such as the recording industry, RIAA, MPAA, and the government are unable to delete or stop the sharing of content on P2P systems.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In P2P networks, clients both provide and use resources.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] This means that unlike client–server systems, the content-serving capacity of peer-to-peer networks can actually *increase* as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as BitTorrent that require users to share, refer a performance measurement study).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Peer-to-peer file sharing networks such as Gnutella, G2, and the eDonkey network have been useful in popularizing peer-to-peer technologies.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] These advancements have paved the way for Peer-to-peer content delivery networks and services, including distributed caching systems like Correli Caches to enhance performance.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Furthermore, peer-to-peer networks have made possible the software publication and distribution, enabling efficient sharing of Linux distribution and various games through file sharing networks.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Peer-to-peer networking involves data transfer from one user to another without using an intermediate server.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Companies developing P2P applications have been involved in numerous legal cases, primarily in the United States, over conflicts with copyright law.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Two major cases are *Grokster vs RIAA* and *MGM Studios, Inc. v.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In the last case, the Court unanimously held that defendant peer-to-peer file sharing companies Grokster and Streamcast could be sued for inducing copyright infringement.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The P2PTV and PDTP protocols are used in various peer-to-peer applications.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Some proprietary multimedia applications leverage a peer-to-peer network in conjunction with streaming servers to stream audio and video to their clients.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Peercasting is employed for multicasting streams.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Additionally, a project called LionShare, undertaken by Pennsylvania State University, MIT, and Simon Fraser University, aims to facilitate file sharing among educational institutions globally.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Another notable program, Osiris, enables users to create anonymous and autonomous web portals that are distributed via a peer-to-peer network.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Cryptocurrency systems are built around a distributed network of nodes that propagate transactions and blocks and maintain a shared ledger.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] According to the National Institute of Standards and Technology, blockchain networks operate in a peer-to-peer fashion, with geographically distributed nodes contributing to the resilience and operation of the system.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Many users interact with these networks using light clients (also referred to as lightweight wallets), which do not operate as full nodes.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Instead, light clients obtain blockchain data and submit transactions by querying full nodes or dedicated servers using a client–server model.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Dat is a distributed version-controlled publishing platform.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] I2P, is an overlay network used to browse the Internet anonymously.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Unlike the related I2P, the Tor network is not itself peer-to-peer; however, it can enable peer-to-peer applications to be built on top of it via onion services.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The InterPlanetary File System (IPFS) is a protocol and network designed to create a content-addressable, peer-to-peer method of storing and sharing hypermedia distribution protocol, with nodes in the IPFS network forming a distributed file system.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Jami is a peer-to-peer chat and SIP app.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] JXTA is a peer-to-peer protocol designed for the Java platform.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Netsukuku is a Wireless community network designed to be independent from the Internet.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Open Garden is a connection-sharing application that shares Internet access with other devices using Wi-Fi or Bluetooth.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Resilio Sync and Syncthing are file synchronization applications.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Research includes projects such as the Chord project, the PAST storage utility, the P-Grid, and the CoopNet content distribution system.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Secure Scuttlebutt is a peer-to-peer gossip protocol capable of supporting many different types of applications, primarily social networking.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Tradepal l and M-commerce applications are designed to power real-time marketplaces.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Department of Defense is conducting research on P2P networks as part of its modern network warfare strategy.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In May 2003, Anthony Tether, then director of DARPA, testified that the United States military uses P2P networks.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] WebTorrent is a P2P streaming torrent client in JavaScript for use in web browsers, as well as in the WebTorrent Desktop standalone version that bridges WebTorrent and BitTorrent serverless networks.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Microsoft, in Windows 10, uses a proprietary peer-to-peer technology called "Delivery Optimization" to deploy operating system updates using end-users' PCs either on the local network or other PCs.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] According to Microsoft's Channel 9, this led to a 30%-50% reduction in Internet bandwidth usage.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Artisoft's LANtastic was built as a peer-to-peer operating system where machines can function as both servers and workstations simultaneously.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Hotline Communications Hotline Client was built with decentralized servers and tracker software dedicated to any type of files and continues to operate today.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Cooperation among a community of participants is key to the continued success of P2P systems aimed at casual human users; these reach their full potential only when large numbers of nodes contribute resources.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] But in current practice, P2P networks often contain large numbers of users who utilize resources shared by other nodes, but who do not share anything themselves (often referred to as the "freeloader problem").
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Freeloading can have a profound impact on the network and in some cases can cause the community to collapse.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In these types of networks "users have natural disincentives to cooperate because cooperation consumes their own resources and may degrade their own performance".
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Studying the social attributes of P2P networks is challenging due to large populations of turnover, asymmetry of interest and zero-cost identity.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] A variety of incentive mechanisms have been implemented to encourage or even force nodes to contribute resources.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Ongoing research efforts for designing effective incentive mechanisms in P2P systems, based on principles from game theory, are beginning to take on a more psychological and information-processing direction.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Hyphanet) place a heavy emphasis on privacy and anonymity—that is, ensuring that the contents of communications are hidden from eavesdroppers, and that the identities/locations of the participants are concealed.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Public key cryptography can be used to provide encryption, data validation, authorization, and authentication for data/messages.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Onion routing and other mix network protocols (e.g.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Tarzan) can be used to provide anonymity.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Perpetrators of live streaming sexual abuse and other cybercrimes have used peer-to-peer platforms to carry out activities with anonymity.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Although peer-to-peer networks can be used for legitimate purposes, rights holders have targeted peer-to-peer over the involvement with sharing copyrighted material.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Companies developing P2P applications have been involved in numerous legal cases, primarily in the United States, primarily over issues surrounding copyright law.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Grokster, Ltd.* In both of the cases the file sharing technology was ruled to be legal as long as the developers had no ability to prevent the sharing of the copyrighted material.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] To establish criminal liability for the copyright infringement on peer-to-peer systems, the government must prove that the defendant infringed a copyright willingly for the purpose of personal financial gain or commercial advantage.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Fair use exceptions allow limited use of copyrighted material to be downloaded without acquiring permission from the rights holders.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] These documents are usually news reporting or under the lines of research and scholarly work.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Controversies have developed over the concern of illegitimate use of peer-to-peer networks regarding public safety and national security.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] When a file is downloaded through a peer-to-peer network, it is impossible to know who created the file or what users are connected to the network at a given time.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Trustworthiness of sources is a potential security threat that can be seen with peer-to-peer systems.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] A study ordered by the European Union found that illegal downloading *may* lead to an increase in overall video game sales because newer games charge for extra features or levels.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The paper concluded that piracy had a negative financial impact on movies, music, and literature.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The study relied on self-reported data about game purchases and use of illegal download sites.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Pains were taken to remove effects of false and misremembered responses.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Peer-to-peer applications present one of the core issues in the network neutrality controversy.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Internet service providers (ISPs) have been known to throttle P2P file-sharing traffic due to its high-bandwidth usage.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Compared to Web browsing, e-mail or many other uses of the internet, where data is only transferred in short intervals and relative small quantities, P2P file-sharing often consists of relatively heavy bandwidth usage due to ongoing file transfers and swarm/network coordination packets.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] In October 2007, Comcast, one of the largest broadband Internet providers in the United States, started blocking P2P applications such as BitTorrent.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Their rationale was that P2P is mostly used to share illegal content, and their infrastructure is not designed for continuous, high-bandwidth traffic.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Critics point out that P2P networking has legitimate legal uses, and that this is another way that large providers are trying to control use and content on the Internet, and direct people towards a client–server-based application architecture.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The client–server model provides financial barriers-to-entry to small publishers and individuals, and can be less efficient for sharing large files.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] As a reaction to this bandwidth throttling, several P2P applications started implementing protocol obfuscation, such as the BitTorrent protocol encryption.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Techniques for achieving "protocol obfuscation" involves removing otherwise easily identifiable properties of protocols, such as deterministic byte sequences and packet sizes, by making the data look as if it were random.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The ISP's solution to the high bandwidth is P2P caching, where an ISP stores the part of files most accessed by P2P clients in order to save access to the Internet.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Researchers have used computer simulations to aid in understanding and evaluating the complex behaviors of individuals within the network.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] "Networking research often relies on simulation in order to test and evaluate new ideas.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] An important requirement of this process is that results must be reproducible so that other researchers can replicate, validate, and extend existing work." If the research cannot be reproduced, then the opportunity for further research is hindered.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] "Even though new simulators continue to be released, the research community tends towards only a handful of open-source simulators.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] The demand for features in simulators, as shown by our criteria and survey, is high.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Therefore, the community should work together to get these features in open-source software.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Popular simulators that were widely used in the past are NS2, OMNeT++, SimPy, NetLogo, PlanetLab, ProtoPeer, QTM, PeerSim, ONE, P2PStrmSim, PlanetSim, GNUSim, and Bharambe.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] Besides all the above stated facts, there has also been work done on ns-2 open source network simulators.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/peer-to-peer] One research issue related to free rider detection and punishment has been explored using ns-2 simulator here.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/real-time-communication] Hard real-time communication systems are frequently electromechanically linked to a physical mechanism, often one that interfaces directly with people or property, which often contributes to or defines the potential danger of a fault.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/real-time-communication] Due to their safety-critical nature, the communication protocols defined in a hard real-time system generally must be deterministic.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/real-time-communication] Hard real-time communication systems are particularly common in the transportation, industrial, and medical sectors.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/real-time-communication] Common applications include control systems, automotive controllers, medical devices, and critical safety systems such as airbag firing computers.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/real-time-communication] Unlike hard real-time communication systems, soft real-time communication systems generally do not have the capacity to cause catastrophic harm upon a fault, which allows for non-deterministic, less rigorous network infrastructure.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/real-time-communication] This allows soft real-time communication systems to operate over consumer networks such as residential internet connections and cellular networks.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/real-time-communication] A large amount of soft real-time systems are telecommunications products such as VoIP systems and certain video calling platforms such as Discord and Google Meet.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/real-time-communication] Data transmitted over a soft real-time communication system is not stored in a centralized server, and peers are connected directly to one another rather than through a server, although intermediary connecting nodes between peers are allowed when a direct link cannot be established.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] The **Session Description Protocol** (**SDP**) is a format for describing multimedia communication sessions for the purposes of announcement and invitation.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Its predominant use is in support of streaming media applications, such as voice over IP (VoIP) and video conferencing.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] SDP does not deliver any media streams itself but is used between endpoints for negotiation of network metrics, media types, and other associated properties.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] The set of properties and parameters is called a *session profile*.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] SDP is extensible for the support of new media types and formats.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] SDP was originally a component of the Session Announcement Protocol (SAP), but found other uses in conjunction with the Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP), the Real-time Streaming Protocol (RTSP), Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), and as a standalone protocol for describing multicast sessions.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] The IETF published the original specification as a Proposed Standard in April 1998 (RFC 2327).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Revised specifications were released in 2006 (RFC 4566), and in 2021 (RFC 8866).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] The Session Description Protocol describes a session as a group of fields in a text-based format, one field per line.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Where `<character>` is a single case-sensitive character and `<value>` is structured text in a format that depends on the character.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed immediately to either side of the equal sign.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Session descriptions consist of three sections: session, timing, and media descriptions.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Each description may contain multiple timing and media descriptions.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Names are only unique within the associated syntactic construct.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Below is a sample session description from RFC 4566.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] This session is originated by the user "jdoe", at IPv4 address 10.47.16.5.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Its name is "SDP Seminar" and extended session information ("A Seminar on the session description protocol") is included along with a link for additional information and an email address to contact the responsible party, Jane Doe.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] This session is specified to last for two hours using NTP timestamps, with a connection address (which indicates the address clients must connect to or — when a multicast address is provided, as it is here — subscribe to) specified as IPv4 224.2.17.12 with a TTL of 127.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Recipients of this session description are instructed to only receive media.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Two media descriptions are provided, both using RTP Audio Video Profile.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] The first is an audio stream on port 49170 using RTP/AVP payload type 0 (defined by RFC 3551 as PCMU), and the second is a video stream on port 51372 using RTP/AVP payload type 99 (defined as "dynamic").
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Finally, an attribute is included which maps RTP/AVP payload type 99 to format h263-1998 with a 90 kHz clock rate.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] RTCP ports for the audio and video streams of 49171 and 51373, respectively, are implied.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] The SDP specification is purely a format for session description.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] It is intended to be distributed over different transport protocols as necessary, including SAP, SIP, and RTSP.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] SDP could even be transmitted by email or as an HTTP payload.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] SDP uses attributes to extend the core protocol.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Attributes can appear within the Session or Media sections and are scoped accordingly as *session-level* or *media-level*.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] New attributes are added to the standard occasionally through registration with IANA.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] The parameters *v*, *s*, and *o* are mandatory, must not be empty, and should be UTF-8-encoded.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] They are used as identifiers and are not intended to be displayed to users.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] A few other attributes are also present in the example, either as a session-level attribute (such as the attribute in property form *a=recvonly*), or as a media-level attribute (such as the attribute in value form *a=rtpmap:99 h263-1998/90000* for the video in the example).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Absolute times are represented in Network Time Protocol (NTP) format (the number of seconds since 1900).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] If the stop time is 0 then the session is *unbounded*.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] If the start time is also zero then the session is considered *permanent*.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Unbounded and permanent sessions are discouraged but not prohibited.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Intervals can be represented with NTP times or in typed time: a value and time units (days: *d*, hours: *h*, minutes: *m* and seconds: *s*) sequence.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] When repeat times are specified, the start time of each repetition may need to be adjusted to compensate for daylight saving time changes so that it will occur at the same local time in a specific time zone throughout the period between the start time and the stop time.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] All these offsets are relative to the start time, they are not cumulative.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] NTP supports this with field *z*, which indicates a series of pairs whose first item is the NTP absolute time when a daylight adjustment will occur, and the second item indicates the offset to apply relative to the absolute times computed with the field *r*.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] For example, if a daylight adjustment will subtract 1 hour on 31 October 2010 at 3 am UTC (i.e.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] If the weekly 1-hour session was repeated every Sunday for one full year, i.e. from Sunday 1 August 2010 3 am UTC to Sunday 26 June 2011 4 am UTC (stop time of the last repeat, i.e.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] As SDP announcements for repeated sessions should not be made to cover very long periods exceeding a few years, the number of daylight adjustments to include in the z= parameter should remain small.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] Sessions may be repeated irregularly over a week but scheduled the same way for all weeks in the period, by adding more tuples in the *r* parameter.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/session-description-protocol] The SDP protocol does not support repeating sessions monthly and yearly schedules with such simple repeat times, because they are irregularly spaced in time; instead, additional *t*/*r* tuples may be supplied for each month or year.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] Supported by Apple, Google, Microsoft, Mozilla, and Opera, WebRTC specifications have been published by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) and the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] ICE, STUN and TURN are the NAT traversal techniques used to connect to remote peers.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] In May 2010, Google bought Global IP Solutions or GIPS, a VoIP and videoconferencing software company that had developed many components required for RTC, such as codecs and echo cancellation techniques.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] Google open-sourced the GIPS technology and engaged with relevant standards bodies at the IETF and W3C to ensure industry consensus.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] In May 2011, Google released an open-source project for browser-based real-time communication known as WebRTC.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] This has been followed by ongoing work to standardize the relevant protocols in the IETF and browser APIs in the W3C.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] In January 2011, Ericsson Labs built the first implementation of WebRTC using a modified WebKit library.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] In October 2011, the W3C published its first draft for the spec.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] WebRTC milestones include the first cross-browser video call (February 2013), first cross-browser data transfers (February 2014), and as of July 2014 Google Hangouts was "kind of" using WebRTC.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] The W3C draft API was based on preliminary work done in the WHATWG.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] It was referred to as the ConnectionPeer API, and a pre-standards concept implementation was created at Ericsson Labs.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] In November 2017, the WebRTC 1.0 specification transitioned from Working Draft to Candidate Recommendation.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] In January 2021, the WebRTC 1.0 specification transitioned from Candidate Recommendation to Recommendation.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] The WebRTC API includes **no provisions for signaling**, that is discovering peers to connect to and determine how to establish connections among them.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] Applications use Interactive Connectivity Establishment for connections and are responsible for managing sessions, possibly relying on any of Session Initiation Protocol, Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol (XMPP), Message Queuing Telemetry Transport, Matrix, or another protocol.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] Signaling may depend on one or more servers.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] RFC 7478 requires implementations to provide PCMA/PCMU (RFC 3551), Telephone Event as DTMF (RFC 4733), and Opus (RFC 6716) audio codecs as minimum capabilities.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] The PeerConnection, data channel and media capture browser APIs are detailed in the W3C specification.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] W3C is developing ORTC (Object Real-Time Communications) for WebRTC.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] WebRTC allows browsers to stream files directly to one another, reducing or entirely removing the need for server-side file hosting.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] WebTorrent uses a WebRTC transport to enable peer-to-peer file sharing using the BitTorrent protocol in the browser.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] Some file-sharing websites use it to allow users to send files directly to one another in their browsers, although this requires the uploader to keep the tab open until the file has been downloaded.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] A few CDNs, such as the Microsoft-owned Peer5, use the client's bandwidth to upload media to other connected peers, enabling each peer to act as an edge server.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] Although initially developed for web browsers, WebRTC has applications for non-browser devices, including mobile platforms and IoT devices.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] Examples include browser-based VoIP telephony, also called cloud phones or web phones, which allow calls to be made and received from within a web browser, replacing the requirement to download and install a softphone.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] WebRTC establishes a standard set of codecs which all compliant browsers are required to implement (underlined).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] Some browsers may also support other codecs.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] In January 2015, TorrentFreak reported a serious security flaw in browsers supporting WebRTC, that compromised the security of VPN tunnels by exposing a user's true IP address.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] The IP address read requests are not visible in the browser's developer console, and they are not blocked by most ad blocking, privacy and security add-ons, enabling online tracking despite precautions.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] It has been reported that the cause of the address leak is not a bug that can be patched, but is foundational to the way WebRTC operates; however, there are several solutions to mitigate the problem.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] WebRTC leakage can be tested for, and solutions are offered for most browsers.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] WebRTC can be disabled, if not required, in most browsers.
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] The uBlock Origin add-on can fix this problem (as some browsers now fix this problem by themselves, from uBlock Origin v1.38 onwards this option has been disabled on these browsers).
[src:webrtc-datachannel/webrtc] Like HTTP3/QUIC, WebRTC cannot be tunneled over TOR because TOR doesn't support UDP, thus most WebRTC applications don't work without bypassing TOR or using TURN servers.
